    <h1>Ban&#xAD;dages off for Gros&#xAD;jean af&#xAD;ter crash</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <time datetime="2021-01-14"><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210114/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-14">2021-01-14</a></time> -
        

            <a href="/category/tag-268490474/en/sg">Incidents</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268448457/en/sg">Accidents</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537281689/en/sg">Paris</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068093/en/sg">Bahrain</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068226/en/sg">Switzerland</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537206244/en/sg">Romain Grosjean</a>     </section>

        <p>PARIS • French driver Ro­main Gros­jean showed his hands fi­nally free of ban­dages on Tues­day, six weeks af­ter a hor­rific fire­ball ac­ci­dent at the Bahrain Grand Prix which forced him to miss the fi­nal two races of last sea­son.</p>
        <p>The 34-year-old, who has now left For­mula One, suf­fered burns to both hands and he has been re­cov­er­ing at his home in Switzer­land.</p>


